[Claude-Opus R3]: # Round 3: The Implementation, and Three Concessions That Shape It

Before code, I settle the R2 exchange honestly.

**Qwen won on polysemy.** My "histogram Hopfield" was incoherent — you cannot run overlap-attention on a scalar count vector. Online context-conditioned routing (route-or-spawn by Jaccard) is correct. Adopted.

**Qwen's Inline Sparse Deflation is half-right and half-fatal.** Subtracting a global baseline `g` to kill the rank-1 component is sound *in spirit* (it's PPMI's "subtract the expected"). But doing it as `counts[idx] -= 1` for every baseline index *on every fold* drives signed counts arbitrarily negative for rare words — a word seen 5 times gets `g` subtracted 5×8=40 times, burying its real signal under −40 baseline. **Deflation must be subtracted at sparsification time, once, scaled by mass — not accumulated.** I implement that fix below.

**I retract iterated feedback entirely.** Even deflated, online 2nd-order folding couples every word's vector to every neighbor's *evolving* vector, and the deflation baseline `g` itself drifts. The convergence proof nobody has produced. So the implementation below is **first-order folding** (neighbor *trigram* anchors, stable) **plus deflation at read** (which captures the 2nd-order PPMI signal *without* the coupling). This is the only thing with a stability argument that survives R2.

**Convergence criterion:** pairwise discrimination margin (~650 occ/word, my R2), not top-k set stability. The Head/Tail split is unnecessary if we never demand set stability — but I keep a weaker version of it for index-churn control, justified below.

---

## The SemanticMemory struct

```rust
use std::collections::HashMap;

const D: u32 = 16384;
const K: usize = 64;              // sem top-k
const W: usize = 4;               // context radius
const FREEZE_OCC: u32 = 650;      // pairwise-discrimination threshold (R2 Claude)
const SPAWN_THRESHOLD: f32 = 0.25;// polysemy route-or-spawn (R2 Qwen)
const MAX_SENSES: usize = 4;
const SHIFT_STEP: u32 = 101;      // coprime with D=16384, role binding

/// One semantic sense of one word.
struct SemProfile {
    // Sparse accumulator, parallel sorted arrays (Qwen: cache locality over HashMap).
    indices: Vec<u32>,            // sorted
    counts:  Vec<u32>,            // counts[j] for indices[j]
    n_occ:   u32,                 // contexts folded into THIS sense
    cached_topk: Option<Box<[u32]>>,
    cache_epoch: u32,             // global_df epoch at which cache was built
}

/// All senses for one word.
struct WordSenses {
    senses: Vec<SemProfile>,      // len 1 for monosemous, up to MAX_SENSES
    frozen: bool,                 // raw accumulators discarded after freeze
}

pub struct SemanticMemory {
    // word_id -> senses
    words: Vec<WordSenses>,

    // Global document frequency per index, for IDF + deflation baseline.
    global_df: Vec<u32>,          // len D
    total_contexts: u64,
    df_epoch: u32,                // bumped on every batch; invalidates caches lazily

    // Parallel sem inverted index: index -> sorted Vec<word_id> (HEAD indices only).
    // 64 shards by (index % 64). Routing is on the HEAD (top-16) only -> low churn.
    sem_index: Vec<Vec<u32>>,     // len D; postings are word_ids whose HEAD contains this index

    // Reference to lexical layer (trigram anchors) — unchanged AtomMemory.
    // We only need read access to a word's trigram vector here.
}

const K_HEAD: usize = 16;         // shard-routing indices (Qwen Head/Tail, weakened use)
```

**Why Head/Tail survives in weakened form.** I rejected Qwen's claim that Head stability *requires* 12k occurrences — that's the set-stability fallacy again. But Qwen's *operational* point stands: if all 64 indices route into `sem_index`, the postings churn every update. Fix: **route only the top-16 (Head) into the inverted index; keep all 64 for scoring.** The Head of a converged word is its highest-mass, most-stable indices — they jitter least. This is index-engineering, not a convergence claim.

---

## memorize_text — full pipeline, raw text to updated embeddings

```rust
impl SemanticMemory {
    pub fn memorize_text(&mut self, text: &str, lex: &AtomMemory) {
        // (1) Tokenize + ensure lexical anchors exist (existing AtomMemory path).
        let word_ids: Vec<u32> = self.tokenize_and_anchor(text, lex);
        if word_ids.is_empty() { return; }

        // (2) Precompute each word's CONTEXT CONTRIBUTION = its trigram anchor.
        //     First-order folding: stable, no feedback coupling. (R2 survivor.)
        //     We clone refs, not data, by indexing lex.
        // (3) Slide window; build per-target context bundle; route to sense; fold.
        for i in 0..word_ids.len() {
            let target = word_ids[i];

            // Build this occurrence's context bundle (shifted trigram union, weighted).
            // Small: <= 2*W*K = 512 entries before dedup. Use a stack-friendly Vec.
            let mut ctx_idx: Vec<u32> = Vec::with_capacity(2 * W * K);
            for d in 1..=W {
                let w = (W + 1 - d) as u32;                 // distance decay 4..1
                let shift = (d as u32 * SHIFT_STEP) % D;     // role binding by position
                if i >= d {
                    push_shifted(&mut ctx_idx, lex.trigrams(word_ids[i - d]), shift, w);
                }
                if i + d < word_ids.len() {
                    // right side: use a DIFFERENT shift sign so "dog bites man" != reverse
                    let rshift = D - shift;                   // inverse permutation
                    push_shifted(&mut ctx_idx, lex.trigrams(word_ids[i + d]), rshift, w);
                }
            }
            // Collapse to sorted unique (idx -> summed weight) — the context vector.
            let (cb_idx, cb_w) = collapse_weighted(&mut ctx_idx);

            // (4) Update global DF (for IDF + deflation) from this context.
            for &idx in &cb_idx { self.global_df[idx as usize] += 1; }
            self.total_contexts += 1;

            // (5) Polysemy routing (R2 Qwen): pick winning sense or spawn.
            let ws = &mut self.words[target as usize];
            if ws.frozen {
                // frozen: only check drift, do not accumulate (cheap path).
                if self.is_drift(target, &cb_idx) { self.thaw(target); }
                else { continue; }
            }
            let sense_id = route_or_spawn(ws, &cb_idx);

            // (6) Fold context into chosen sense's accumulator (sorted merge, O(k)).
            let s = &mut self.words[target as usize].senses[sense_id];
            merge_weighted(&mut s.indices, &mut s.counts, &cb_idx, &cb_w);
            s.n_occ += 1;
            s.cached_topk = None;

            // (7) Freeze check: discard raw accumulator once discrimination locks.
            let total_occ: u32 = self.words[target as usize]
                .senses.iter().map(|x| x.n_occ).sum();
            if total_occ >= FREEZE_OCC && !self.words[target as usize].frozen {
                self.freeze(target);   // builds final top-k, inserts HEAD into sem_index,
                                       // drops indices/counts Vecs -> 256 B/word steady state
            }
        }
        self.df_epoch += 1;            // lazy cache invalidation for sparsify
    }
}
```

### Helpers (the hot loop)

```rust
#[inline]
fn push_shifted(out: &mut Vec<u32>, trigrams: &[u32], shift: u32, weight: u32) {
    // Encode weight by repeating? No — we carry weight separately in collapse.
    // Here we just push (idx+shift)%D; weight applied in collapse via a parallel pass.
    // To keep weight, we push the index `weight` times is wasteful; instead we tag.
    // Simpler: push raw, then collapse adds W per occurrence. We store weight inline:
    for &t in trigrams {
        out.push(((t + shift) % D) << 3 | (weight & 0x7)); // pack weight in low 3 bits
    }
}

#[inline]
fn collapse_weighted(buf: &mut Vec<u32>) -> (Vec<u32>, Vec<u32>) {
    buf.sort_unstable();
    let mut idx = Vec::with_capacity(buf.len());
    let mut wts = Vec::with_capacity(buf.len());
    let mut j = 0;
    while j < buf.len() {
        let real = buf[j] >> 3;
        let mut acc = 0u32;
        while j < buf.len() && (buf[j] >> 3) == real {
            acc += buf[j] & 0x7;
            j += 1;
        }
        idx.push(real);
        wts.push(acc);
    }
    (idx, wts)   // sorted-u32 invariant preserved
